Informal statement: The sine of the real number $\pi$, denoted as $\sin(\pi)$, is equal to 0. This is a fundamental result in trigonometry that arises from the periodicity of the sine function and the definition of $\pi$ as the smallest positive real number for which $\cos(\pi) = 0$, which implies that $\sin(\pi) = 0$ due to the half-angle relationship between sine and cosine.
